SIMPLE: lordly
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lordly
<hw>Lord"ly</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Lordlier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Lordliest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[<ets>Lord</ets> +
<ets>-ly</ets>. Cf. <er>Lordlike</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Suitable
for a lord; of or pertaining to a lord; resembling a lord; hence, grand;
noble; dignified; honorable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She brought forth butter in a <qex>lordly</qex> dish.</q>
<rj><qau>Judges v. 25.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Lordly</qex> sins require <qex>lordly</qex> estates to
support them.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The maidens gathered strength and grace⟦br⟧
And presence, <qex>lordlier</qex> than before.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Proud; haughty; imperious; insolent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lords are <qex>lordliest</qex> in their wine.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Imperious; haughty; overbearing; tyrannical;
despotic; domineering; arrogant. See <er>Imperious</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lordly</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lordly
<hw>Lord"ly</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In a lordly manner.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lordolatry</ent>⟦br⟧
